One of the most famous religious places in the town.

The magnificent work of art, Built-in during the rule of Ahmed Shah. The architecture is a beautiful combination of Islamic & Hindu Architecture.

The mesmerising and huge courtyard is made of white marbles, a perfect spot for excellent photography.

If you are in town during ramadan, go visit here. It's the most crowded praying place. The experience of praying here is itself a kind. I visited on weekdays and found it was a peaceful place with no disturbance at all. No parking facility though, for a popular spot.
Attaching photos and videos for your reference.

A few days ago, I visited Ahmedabad and saw the Jama Masjid for the first time. It is an incredibly large and beautiful mosque, meticulously maintained and exceptionally clean. The architecture and intricate design were awe-inspiring. The moment I entered, I was captivated by the serene ambiance and the sense of history that enveloped the place. The grandeur of the courtyard and the imposing domes left me spellbound.

The Jama Masjid is a true testament to the rich cultural heritage of Ahmedabad and a place that fills one's heart with a deep sense of reverence. The attention to detail in its construction and the exquisite craftsmanship are evident in every nook and corner. The sight of the beautiful prayer hall and the finely adorned minarets is something that I will cherish for a long time.

Furthermore, the cleanliness and organization of the mosque reflect the devotion and care of the people who maintain it. The surroundings were well-kept, creating a peaceful and inviting atmosphere for visitors like me.

Overall, my experience at the Jama Masjid in Ahmedabad was unforgettable. It stands as a symbol of architectural brilliance and religious significance, and I am grateful for the opportunity to witness such a magnificent and sacred place. If you ever find yourself in Ahmedabad, I highly recommend visiting this extraordinary marvel.

featured_reviews.review_id:
A great place to visit. This is a peaceful place where the architecture is wonderful. There was hardly any one present when we went there . A compulsory place to visit in ahmedabad.

Sarkhej Roza is a mosque and tomb complex located in the village of Makarba, 7 km south-west of Ahmedabad in Gujarat state, India.

Although there are many rozas across Gujarat, the Sarkhej Roza is the most revered. Sarkhej was once a prominent centre of Sufi culture in the country, where influential Sufi saint Shaikh Ahmed Ganj Baksh lived. It was on the saint's suggestion that Sultan Ahmed Shah set up his capital on the banks of the Sabarmati, a few miles away from Sarkhej.

Like many monuments built during that period, the Sarkhej Roza fused both non-Indian and Indian principles of architecture. While the ringed domes, the profusion of pillars and brackets can be claimed to follow the Islamic west Asian genre (even though they can also be found in Indian architecture itself since much before), much of the ornamentation and motifs have Indian Hindu designs. Most of the buildings do not have arches and depend on pierced stone trellises for stability. In its architecture, Sarkhej Roza is an example of the early Islamic architectural culture of the region, which fused Islamic stylistic influences from Persia with Indian Hindu and Jain features to form a composite Indo-Saracenic architectural style. The mosque, with its courtyard, creates a religious milieu; the royal connection is made through the tombs and palaces; the great tank, platforms and pavilions were used by the common man.

The complex is called "Acropolis of Ahmedabad", due to 20th century architect Le Corbusier's comparison of this complex's design to the Acropolis of Athens.
